properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for today. An intense band of snow associated with the passage of a cold front is expected to move across Far Northern Ontario today. This band of snow may extend from Winisk River Provincial Park to Weagamow Lake this afternoon and is expected to move southward throughout the day, reaching Lansdowne House to Cat Lake by this evening. A total snowfall accumulation up to 10 cm is possible. Hazardous travel conditions are expected due to near zero visibilities in bursts of heavy snow and blowing snow. Consider post-poning non essential travel until conditions improve. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong northwest winds 70 km/h gusting to 90 to return early this evening. Currently, winds over areas of Metro Vancouver near the southern Strait of Georgia , and Southern Gulf Islands will continue to be strong, with speeds peaking around 50 km/h gusting to 70. With the ridge of high pressure continuing to build off Vancouver Island; it will bring another round of stronger northwesterly winds with speeds of 70 km/h gusting to 90 along the southern Strait of Georgia early this evening. The strong winds will gradually ease below warning levels late this evening, then to light overnight. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of very cold wind chills is expected. A cold arctic airmass settling over Manitoba is causing a prolonged period of extreme wind chill values. This cold airmass will caused overnight wind chill values to reach extreme cold criteria of -45 and colder. These extreme wind chill values will moderate somewhat during the day, but will return over the next few nights. Extreme cold warnings will likely end Sunday morning. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Sant at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257.
